    <text xml:space="preserve">
        
        <body>
            
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="tam-Latn" rendition="class:tamil maturity:vernacular">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><hi rend="grantha">svasti śrī</hi>
                </ab>
                
                <p>
                    Inta nitta
                    <lb n="2" break="no"/>-maṇṭapañ ceyvi
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/>ttāṉ Āṟṟ<supplied reason="omitted">ūr</supplied>-uṭai
                    <lb n="4" break="no"/><unclear>y</unclear>āṉ cunta<choice><orig>n</orig><reg>ṉ</reg></choice> paṭṭa
                    <lb n="5" break="no"/><choice><orig>n</orig><reg>ṉ</reg></choice>-āṉa tillai-nāyaka
                    <lb n="6" break="no"/>-vēḻāṉ                    
                </p>
                
            </div>
            
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    
                    <app loc="3">
                        <lem>Āṟṟ<supplied reason="omitted">ūr</supplied>uṭai<lb n="4" break="no"/><unclear>y</unclear>āṉ</lem>
                        <note>See <foreign>Āṟṟūruṭaiyāṉ</foreign> in <ref target="DHARMA_INSTamilNadu00045"/>, line 2.</note>
                    </app>      
                    
                </listApp>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation" resp="part:reda part:emfr">
                
                <p n="1"> 		
                    Prosperity! Fortune!
                </p>
                
                <p n="1-6">
                    He who had this dancing <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>nittam</foreign></supplied><note>From the Sanskrit <foreign>nṛtta/nṛtya</foreign>.</note> <foreign>maṇḍapa</foreign> made is Tillai Nāyaka Vēḷāṉ <hi rend="italic">alias</hi> Cuntaṉ<note>That is, Cuntaraṉ? But see Cuntapaṭṭaṉ in <ref target="DHARMA_INSTamilNadu00045"/>.</note> Paṭṭaṉ, lord of Āṟṟūr.
                </p>
                
            </div>
            
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Compare with <ref target="INSSIIv12p0i0178"/>, a 13th century inscription from Jambai (Tirukkōvilūr) where another construction of a dancing hall (<foreign>nitta maṇḍapa</foreign>) is registered.</p>
                <p>Compare with <ref target="DHARMA_INSTamilNadu00045"/>, of similar content, of the time of Poṉparappināṉ alias Rājarāja. It is not clear if the <foreign>maṇḍapa</foreign> referred to in both inscriptions is the same one as <ref target="DHARMA_INSTamilNadu00045"/> is on the wall of the <foreign>mukhamaṇḍapa</foreign> and this inscription is on a pillar of the open <foreign>maṇḍapa</foreign> in front of the <foreign>mukhamaṇḍapa</foreign>.</p> 
            </div>
            
            <div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Not reported, but see <bibl><ptr target="bib:ARIE1939-1943"/></bibl> (ARIE/1939-1943/B/1940-1941/159), that is, <ref target="DHARMA_INSTamilNadu00045"/>, of similar content.</p>
                <p>This edition by Renato Dávalos and Emmanuel Francis, based on autopsy (2024) and photos (E. Francis, 2024).</p>	
                
